1065C 101st Legislative Session 1065
2026 South Dakota Legislature
House Bill 1065
AMENDME NT 1065C
FOR THE INTRODUCED BILL
Introduced by: Representative Ismay
1 An Act to require the possession of a registry identification card to raise an revise
2 the medical purpose affirmative defense in cannabis prosecution.
3 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF SOUTH DAKOTA:
4 Section 1. That § 34-20G-51 be AMENDED:
5 34-20G-51. Except as provided in § 34-20G-18 and this section, a person may
6 assert the medical purpose for using cannabis as a defense to any prosecution involving
7 cannabis, and such defense is presumed valid where the evidence shows that:
8 (1) A practitioner has stated that, in the practitioner's professional opinion, after
9 having completed a full assessment of the person's medical history and current
10 medical condition made in the course of a bona fide practitioner-patient
11 relationship, the patient has a debilitating medical condition and the potential
12 benefits of using cannabis for medical purposes would likely outweigh the health
13 risks for the person;
14 (2) The person was in possession of no more than three ounces of cannabis, the
15 amount of cannabis products allowed by department rules, two flowering cannabis
16 plants, two cannabis plants that are not flowering, and the cannabis produced by
17 those plants;
18 (3) The person was engaged in the acquisition, possession, use, manufacture,
19 cultivation, or transportation of cannabis, paraphernalia, or both, relating to the
20 administration of cannabis to treat or alleviate the person's debilitating medical
21 condition or symptoms associated with the person's debilitating medical condition;
22 and
23 (4) Any cultivation of cannabis and storage of more than three ounces of cannabis
24 occurred in a secure location that only the person asserting the defense could
25 access
26
Underscores indicate new language.
Overstrikes indicate deleted language.

1065C 2 1065
1 (1) If the person is a:
2 (a) Qualifying patient, the person was registered with the department as a
3 cardholder or nonresident cardholder at the time of the alleged offense; or
4 (b) Designated caregiver, the person was registered with the department as a
5 designated caregiver at the time of the alleged offense; and
6 (2) The conduct underlying the alleged offense complied with this chapter.
7 Section 2. That § 34-20G-53 be AMENDED:
8 34-20G-53. A person is not required to possess a registry identification card to raise the
9 affirmative defense set forth in § 34-20G-51.
10 Section 2. That § 34-20G-53 be REPEALED.
11 A person is not required to possess a registry identification card to raise the
12 affirmative defense set forth in § 34-20G-51.
